All told, the theories of participation and the factors that directly influence participation in the consultation processes are numerous and complex. Elected civic officials and municipal staffs both, have a different range of motivations for organizing consultation. There are a myriad of statements about why public participation is sought, but the statement of benefits set out by Involve, a British nongovernmental organization that promotes consultation, is typical:



understanding people’s needs, preferences, and values by talking with them is a way to enhance the effectiveness of decision making and service provision;



involving people in the decisions that affect them can increase the legitimacy of those decisions among participants and more widely;



some public services may need active participation to be effective (Baker, Coaffee, and Sherriff 2007, 80).

It is felt that a failure to include the public or validate their opinions can render them “vexatious and cynical” (Berman 1997, 110) “while depriving decision makers of input and compromising legitimacy” (Walters, Aydelotte, and Miller 2000, 357). As noble and commendable as such statements are, the devil as always is in the details. Questions have arisen from the start about how much understanding of people’s needs and values is enough, about how much people can really be involved in decisions that are often highly technical, and about how much participation is needed to be effective? Having reviewed the literature that addresses the theoretical aspects of public participation, we will now turn to discussion of what techniques have been developed and evolved since public consultation first appeared before turning to the means researchers have used to evaluate what is actually being done.
